\noindent \textbf{Problem 1}: In this exercise I will ask you to construct the rational numbers and prove it is an ordered field. Define $\mathbb{Q}$ as a \emph{set} as $\mathbb{Z} \times \mathbb{Z}/\sim$, where $\sim$ is the equivalence relation $(p, q) \sim (a, b)$ if there is an integer $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ such that $np = a$ and $nq = b$. \\
a) Distinguish an additive and multiplicative identity on this set.  Note that, somewhat confusingly, these elements will actually be equivalence classes, which are sets. \\
b) Define the addition operator and multiplication operators on this set.  Define additive and multiplicative inversion. \\
c) Show that the operations you have defined satisfy the field axioms. \\
d) Define an order on $\mathbb{Q}$.  Show that the order you defined makes $\mathbb{Q}$ into an ordered field (i.e. prove the properties of an ordered field).
e) Show that there is no rational number $x$ such that $x^2 = 2$, under your construction. \\
f)  Prove the following: let $p < q \in \mathbb{Q}$.  There exists a rational number $x$ such that $p < x < q$.
