\noindent \textbf{Problem 4}: This problem will acquaint you with understanding open and closed sets in metric spaces. \\
a) Give a collection of open sets $A_1, A_2, A_3, \ldots$ such that:
$$\bigcap_{i=1}^\infty A_i$$
is not open.
b) Give a collection of closed sets $A_1, A_2, A_3, \ldots$ such that:
$$\bigcup_{i=1}^\infty A_i$$
is not closed. 
c) Consider the subset $A \subset \mathbb{R}$ defined by $A = \{\frac{1}{n} \mid n \in \mathbb{N}\}$.  Is this set open?  Is it closed? \\
d) It is not true that the closure of the open ball is the closed ball: $\overline{B_\epsilon(x)} = \overline{B}_\epsilon(x)$.  Give an example of a metric space where this is not true. \\


